Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
President Joe Biden is one of the most consequential presidents in American history. ¬†

With the wisdom and magnificent leadership of President Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris, our nation has been graced by four historic years of progress, hope and unity for American families.  

Tonight, President Biden delivered his farewell address to a nation that is stronger because of his leadership.¬† In doing so, he honored the vision of founders, the sacrifice of our men and women in uniform and the aspirations of our children.

With deep experience and with global relationships that are rivaled by none, President Biden has masterfully led America on the world stage.¬† 

Under President Biden‚Äôs visionary leadership, America has been unequivocal in our commitment to defending Democracy here at home and around the world ‚Äì and our NATO alliance is stronger and more unified than ever.¬† 

America was fortunate to have a strong, steady, wise commander-in-chief honoring and promoting American values in the global arena.

President Biden and Vice President Harris, with the partnership of Democrats in Congress, have built a towering legacy of extraordinary achievement for the American people.¬† 

They pulled our nation from the depths of the pandemic and ignited the strongest economic recovery in the world with our American Rescue Plan.¬† 

They seized a once-in-a-century chance to rebuild our nation while investing in our middle class with our Bipartisan Infrastructure Law.¬† 

With our CHIPS and Science Act, they declared America‚Äôs economic independence: powering a manufacturing boom, driving decades of scientific discovery and creating good-paying jobs across the country.¬† 

They enacted America's first major gun violence prevention legislation in nearly three decades with our Bipartisan Safer Communities Act and took a monumental step toward fully honoring the service and sacrifice of our heroes in uniform with our PACT Act.¬† 

With our Inflation Reduction Act, they honored our moral responsibility to save the planet while bringing down costs for working families by lowering prescription drug prices and energy bills.¬† 

And our Respect for Marriage Act was a triumph of love, liberty and justice for all.

President Biden and Vice President Harris have earned their place in the pantheon of American democracy.¬† 

Every American can be proud of the leadership and dignity they brought to the White House ‚Äì and tonight, we again saw President Biden's great respect for America's remarkable history.¬† 

With love and gratitude, I salute President Biden and Vice President Harris for always believing in the possibilities of America and building a stronger and fairer future for all of America's families.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1547, Ivan the Terrible became the first Tsar of Russia. 

His reign saw Russia's transformation from a medieval state to a growing empire, but at a great cost to its people and economy. He enacted reforms, including a new legal code, local self-government, the creation of Russia‚Äôs first standing army, and built relations with Europe. 

Ivan later became more autocratic, purging the nobility through his secret police. His later years were marked by violence. Though often seen as intelligent and devout, Ivan was also prone to extreme paranoia and violent outbursts. Historians believe he murdered his eldest son and heir, Ivan Ivanovich, in a fit of rage, leaving the throne to his weak and childless son Feodor, which led to the collapse of the Rurik dynasty and the onset of the Time of Troubles.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Funding judges, which seems to be an issue for the other side, can fix the asylum process: those fleeing danger can apply safely in a second country, & get a hearing within months, not years.

More folks will get to safety legally & fewer will come here unlawfully (and unsafely).

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
The issue of the border and immigration reform isn‚Äôt simple, rarely are there moral absolutes, and there are certainly no easy answers.

But we are a nation of immigrants - and a nation of laws - and these two facts should help guide us.

6 ways I think we can do this.üßµ‚¨áÔ∏è

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
1. We have to secure the border. This should be first, and we can establish real structure and safety for folks.

I still believe the bipartisan deal makes sense: hire more patrol officers and judges and invest in better technology.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
3. Our communities are dealing with limited resources and Americans are being hurt. Don‚Äôt be xenophobic or hateful, but know it‚Äôs a real issue.

Shelters for battered women are often booked for migrant families. We can't put people in this position, so we secure the border first.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
2. There is bipartisan support for additional, legal pathways. 

American workers should come first, and we should continue to invest in training our people. But when gaps exist, work permits make sense.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
4. This is bad for a lot of the people coming here. 

They‚Äôre sleeping in the desert and then on the street or under a bridge. Staying home would have been better for them, especially if there were legal pathways.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
6. Mass deportations would be a strain on limited local resources.

Law enforcement is stretched thin as local funding has been slashed or not kept up with inflation. We want our police patrolling our streets and keeping us safe, not rounding up families and putting them where?

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
5. If people who have come here unlawfully get arrested for a second crime, they should go home.

Protect DREAMERS who didn‚Äôt do anything wrong, but if you break the law ‚Äì again ‚Äì you go home.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Our jails are full. 

ICE will continue to remove folks who break the law, but neighborhood sweeps won‚Äôt fly in most communities. Plus, who‚Äôs paying for this insanely expensive endeavor? Taxpayers? At the expense of disaster relief for our families?

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: This is just one member of Congress‚Äôs opinion, of course, but I do hope it helps us find common ground and a path forward on one of the most complex and complicated issues we face.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Great meeting with @IATSE International President Matt Loeb to discuss the urgent need to deliver long-overdue tax relief to the talented individuals who bring our entertainment industry to life‚Äîboth on stage and behind the scenes. As a proud champion and co-sponsor of the bipartisan Performing Arts Tax Parity Act, I have been actively working to get this important bill signed into law. 

For nearly 40 years, outdated tax laws have placed an unfair burden on our entertainment professionals, preventing them from accessing the financial relief they deserve. While the tax code acknowledges the upfront costs of this industry, the income thresholds set decades ago no longer reflect today‚Äôs economic realities. Updating these thresholds is critical to ensuring these hardworking individuals can pursue their careers without being crushed by disproportionate tax obligations.

Thank you, Matt, for your advocacy and partnership‚ÄîI look forward to continuing working alongside you, your members, and my colleagues in Congress to get this critical piece of legislation across the finish line.

Name: Crawford, Eric A. "Rick"
text:
I am truly honored to be selected to lead the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence. I look forward to working with Speaker Johnson and the incoming Trump administration team to advance priorities that are important to Americans.

Since joining the Committee in 2017, I have witnessed firsthand that abuse within our nation‚Äôs security apparatus has eroded trust in our institutions and compromised America‚Äôs ability to gather intelligence. As Chairman, I will aggressively uphold our mandate to provide credible and robust oversight of the Intelligence Community‚Äôs funding and activities. Without aggressive oversight and vigorous protection of Americans‚Äô Fourth Amendment rights, the IC is prone to give in to mission creep and skirt U.S. laws. In all our work, I pledge to preserve Americans‚Äô constitutional rights even as we work to support the IC in doing everything required to collect indispensable information from our foreign adversaries.

This Congress has an opportunity to course-correct from the Biden administration‚Äôs failures, promote common-sense peace through strength, and re-focus our nation's intelligence and counterintelligence community against our adversaries. Right now, terrorists, rogue regimes, and foreign state-actors are rapidly developing new ways to exploit and harm America‚Äôs national interests, and it‚Äôs our responsibility to ensure intelligence agencies remain three steps ahead of our enemies. And now, more than ever, leaks and indiscretions by misguided intelligence staff can endanger Americans and hinder our ability to predict and prevent attacks. Everyone on the Committee and within the IC must be devoted to secrecy regarding the material we review. The lives of our covert agents in the field, and the security of our homeland, depend on it.

The Committee has a unique opportunity to work toward rebuilding our intelligence apparatus so that our IC is focused on the challenges of today and is prepared for the threats of tomorrow. It is our aim to rebuild relationships with our partners in the Western Hemisphere, address issues with the development of IC assessments, determine which intelligence tools are needed to protect Americans, and provide our brave men and women in the U.S. intelligence services with the support they need. In our age of increasing threats from abroad and bloated bureaucracy at home, the Committee will be committed to preventing enemies‚Äô attacks and upholding the privacy rights of all American citizens.

I want to thank Chairman Turner for his work in the 118th Congress. He led our committee ably and admirably, at a time when there was a distinct need for a steady hand. He is a valued member of our Conference, and I will build from the solid base his leadership provided this committee.

Since entering Congress, I‚Äôve made it my mission to ensure our nation‚Äôs Rosie the Riveters receive the recognition they rightfully deserve. Leading the passage of the Rosie the Riveter Congressional Gold Medal Act was one of the greatest honors of my career, and presenting the Congressional Gold Medal to some of the incredible living Rosies of Bucks and Montgomery counties, including my dear friend, Mae Krier, was a moment I will never forget. They accepted this historic award on behalf of the millions of Rosies whose unparalleled courage, resilience, and determination helped lead our nation to victory in World War II. These extraordinary women didn‚Äôt just power factories; they powered a nation, igniting a wave of patriotism and paving the way for women‚Äôs empowerment and equality.

Yesterday, I renewed my commitment to honoring their incredible legacy by introducing the Rosie the Riveter Commemorative Coin Act with a bipartisan coalition of my colleagues. This legislation is more than a tribute‚Äîit‚Äôs a lasting reminder of their profound impact. The Rosies‚Äô patriotism and determination shaped the fabric of our nation and continue to inspire every generation that follows.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1966, a B-52 bomber collided with a KC-135 jet tanker off Spain‚Äôs Mediterranean coast, causing the bomber to drop three hydrogen bombs near the town of Palomares and one into the sea. 

The accident, part of the Cold War-era practice of keeping bombers on constant alert, was one of many involving U.S. nuclear weapons. The Pentagon later acknowledged over 30 similar incidents, where bombs were damaged or lost due to crashes or fires.

The B-52, returning from a routine mission, collided with the tanker during refueling, killing all four tanker crew members and causing the B-52 to break apart. Although the bombs were not armed, two exploded on impact, a third was found largely intact, and the fourth bomb was lost at sea.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First 

Corey Gooden, a resident of Edenton, is a true community leader whose influence extends well beyond his responsibilities as the town manager. He demonstrates leadership and compassion through mentoring young people, coaching youth sports, and organizing community events. His active involvement with his church and support for his neighbors underscore his dedication to building a stronger, more connected community.

When Hurricane Helene struck western North Carolina, Corey quickly sprang into action to help restore essential water and sewer services in Old Fort, NC. Deployed twice with NC Emergency Management and NC WaterWARN, he assisted residents without utilities for over nine days. In every joyful or challenging situation, Corey rises to the occasion with steadfast determination and an unwavering commitment to others. We proudly highlight his service and efforts to go above and beyond.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we honor the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district‚Äîindividuals who have made a profound difference in the lives of others. Today, we celebrate a man whose unwavering dedication, courageous leadership, and boundless compassion have shaped the very fabric of our community. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: Lower Makefield Police Chief Ken Coluzzi.
 
From the moment he fulfilled his dream of becoming a police officer in 1978, Ken Coluzzi dedicated himself to protecting and serving others. Over the next 48 years, his career became a masterclass in law enforcement, marked by integrity, determination, and an unrelenting pursuit of justice. Rising through the ranks of the Philadelphia Police Department, he commanded elite investigative units and tackled some of the city‚Äôs most challenging and high-profile cases. His work‚Äîon cases such as the ‚ÄúBoy in the Box‚Äù cold case, the Center City Rapist, and the Pier 34 collapse‚Äînot only brought closure to families but also demonstrated his steadfast commitment to truth and fairness.

Then, in 2000, we welcomed Ken to our Lower Makefield Community to serve as police chief. Throughout his 24 years of service in our community, Chief Coluzzi worked tirelessly to transform the department, expanding its ranks, professionalizing its operations, and fostering a culture rooted in fairness and trust. Under his leadership, the department achieved Pennsylvania State Accreditation and set a gold standard for excellence. His advocacy to equip our local first responders with Narcan has helped to save 42 lives in Lower Makefield alone and has become a model for departments across Bucks County.

Chief Coluzzi‚Äôs impact has extended far beyond his badge; he has served as a source of strength and compassion during times of tragedy and triumph alike. From supporting families affected by 9/11 to advocating for vulnerable members of our community and fostering strong police-community relations, his leadership was defined not just by his ability to protect but his commitment to building trust, unity, and a sense of belonging.
 
As Chief Coluzzi steps into a well-deserved retirement, he leaves behind a legacy that is both profound and enduring. His dedication has touched every corner of Lower Makefield, and made our community not only safer, but truly better.

Chief, on behalf of our entire community, thank you for your remarkable contributions, congratulations on an extraordinary career, and best wishes for a retirement as fulfilling as the legacy you leave behind!

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
In 1776, Thomas Jefferson wrote in the Declaration of Independence that all men were created equal.¬†

72 years later, Elizabeth Cady Stanton wrote the sequel: the Declaration of Sentiments, declaring all men and women were created equal.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text: The U.S. Constitution promised to create a government by, of and for the people, but it did not include everyone. The founding fathers ignored Abigail Adam‚Äôs call to ‚Äúremember the ladies, and be more generous and favorable to them than your ancestors.‚Äù

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
In 1868, the 14th Amendment guaranteed equal protection under the law to all.¬†

But the Supreme Court applied stricter rules for discrimination on the basis of race, religion or national origin than it did on the basis of sex.

This is not true equal protection for all.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
For 102 years, activists have worked to pass the Equal Rights Amendment, an extension of the 14th Amendment‚Äôs promise.¬†

Women of color have been in the fight for equality for all from the beginning, even when relegated to the background and the last to benefit from progress.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
As I previously shared, President Donald Trump and Vice President-Elect JD Vance announced earlier today that the 60th Inaugural Ceremonies will be moved inside the U.S. Capitol Building, in the Rotunda, instead of the previous outdoor plans. 
 
House Leadership and the Sergeant at Arms have informed us that as a result of this change, ticketed guests will NOT be able to attend the ceremonies in person. The 60th Inaugural Ceremonies tickets are now considered commemorative memorabilia.

In his social media post, President Trump has encouraged inauguration ticket holders to view the ceremonies at Capital One Arena on January 20th. President Trump will report to Capital One Arena shortly after the conclusion of the swearing-in ceremony in the Capitol Rotunda. We have not received ANY information regarding admission and timing about this alternative but will communicate this when we are made aware. 

Please know that inauguration tickets do not guarantee seating or entry at Capital One Arena. Again, when we learn more information about the viewing at Capital One Arena, our office will let you know.

Capital One Arena is located at 601 F St NW, Washington, DC 20004.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as our team navigates these changes and works through the details. If you have reached out to us individually, we will do our best to respond as soon as possible.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
I welcome the news of a ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas, which occurred as a result of intense negotiations and diligent work by our allies and partners across the region, aided by the leadership of the Biden Administration. This ceasefire agreement would provide a halt to the conflict that has waged for the last 15 months, ever since Hamas‚Äô brutal attack on Israel, where they killed more than 1,200 people ‚Äì including 46 Americans ‚Äì and captured hundreds of hostages, including Americans. ¬†
¬†
The conflict that followed has killed tens of thousands of Palestinians and displaced millions of people. From Rafah to Tel Aviv, far too many have been impacted by this horrific conflict, and I celebrate the news of a ceasefire. ¬†
¬†
This ceasefire agreement would halt the fighting in Gaza, return the hostages captured by Hamas, ensure Israel‚Äôs security, and provide much-needed humanitarian assistance to civilians in Gaza. This is an extraordinary opportunity to end the violence that has taken far too many lives and threatened the stability of the entire region. Going forward, we must take steps to ensure there is a future of self-governance for the Palestinian people and long-term security for Israel. It is the only path to peace in the region.

text:
The 60th Inaugural Ceremony has been moved inside the Rotunda of the U.S Capitol Building. Because of this, we have received guidance from the JCCIC that there will be no public viewing regardless of ticket holder status. 

See below for their official statement:

‚ÄúThe House Sergeant at Arms (SAA) has been informed by the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies (JCCIC) that the 60th Inaugural Ceremonies will be held inside the U.S. Capitol.

As a result, the majority of ticketed guests will not be able to attend the ceremonies in person, although offices are welcome to distribute tickets to constituents in the manner they think best, if they would like to do so. It is our understanding from the JCCIC that all Members of Congress will be invited to the indoor ceremony. House Members of JCCIC recommend that your offices relay to constituents that their tickets will be commemorative.‚Äù

We wish we did not have deliver this news, as we know so many South Carolinians made travel plans and sacrifices to join us in DC to celebrate President Trump. However, President Trump and the JCCIC believe this is the best course of action to ensure the safety of all guests and participants due to extreme weather in Washington DC.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1803, President Thomas Jefferson requested $2,500 from Congress to fund the Lewis and Clark expedition.

Meriwether Lewis and William Clark led a team of 50 people, including the Native American guide Sacagawea, to explore the vast Louisiana Territory. Their journey surveyed land from present-day North Dakota to Texas, crossed the Rockies, and reached the Pacific coast in Oregon, fueling interest in westward expansion.

Jefferson had proposed such an expedition even before the U.S. acquired the Louisiana Territory from France. Napoleon, seeking funds for his European campaigns, sold the land to the United States. The purchase of 828,000 square miles west of the Mississippi River effectively doubled the size of the country at the time.

I remain steadfast in my determination to pursue the safe return of all remaining hostages to their loved ones and for lasting peace in the region.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
After having met with many people regarding the TikTok issue, it is apparent that what‚Äôs known as a ‚ÄúChinese golden share structure‚Äù is standing in the way of saving TikTok. 

If a company has a ‚Äúgolden share structure ‚Äù it means that one of the shareholders is Xi Jinping, the head of the Chinese Communist Party. He owns you and makes all the decisions. 

While I want TikTok to keep operating in a manner consistent with our national security, it is long past time to deal with the golden share dilemma more broadly. 

I will soon introduce legislation with my Senate colleagues that prevents any company that has a ‚ÄúChinese golden share‚Äù from being listed on any American exchange and further, remove any existing company that has a golden share structure from any American exchange.

text:
Today, as we inaugurate a new president, we also honor the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., a true American hero.

In my office hangs a photo of Dr. King with a small group in a church basement. I show it to visitors, especially young ones, to remind them that he didn't begin with millions listening to his "I Have a Dream" speech on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial.

Dr. King faced immense challenges. He tirelessly organized, fought, and inspired countless individuals to rise above their fears and anger, to work together to build a world grounded in love, truth, and justice.

As we face the dawn of a new administration in a time of deep division, let us be inspired by MLK‚Äôs unwavering hope and determination. Working together, let us heal our divisions and aspire to make America ‚Äúa more perfect union‚Äù that is truly a light to all the world.

On Martin Luther King, Jr. Day, our nation celebrates one of our greatest heroes, whose fierce spirit and clarion voice of truth forever altered the course of history.¬† Dr. King's struggle for civil rights, social and economic justice and equal opportunity advanced our nation in the journey toward a more perfect union. Americans continue to draw inspiration from his unshakable faith, extraordinary courage and unwavering vision for peace.

While our nation has forged important progress on the road to freedom for all of God‚Äôs children, today we are reminded of the urgent work ahead needed to defend our democracy.¬† Dr. King explained as he accepted the Nobel Peace Prize that because of his ‚Äòabiding faith in America and an audacious faith in the future of mankind, [he] refuse[d] to accept despair as the final response to the ambiguities of history.'
¬†
On this National Day of Service, we must refuse to accept despair by carrying on Dr. King's legacy of hope and recommitting our fight to secure the blessings of liberty for every American ‚Äî and always striving to build a future worthy of Dr. King's glorious vision.¬† God truly bless America with the life and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.

text:
Today marks the start of a new Presidential Administration. I congratulate President Trump and hope that we can all work together on behalf of the American people.

There are many challenges facing our country, and we must find a way to tackle them. I am ready to partner with my Republican colleagues on any issue where we can find common ground.

To bring down costs, to build housing, and to create more jobs. To address the crime that is affecting so many and to fix an economy that seems to work best for those at the very top and big corporations. To protect our freedoms, increase opportunity for our families, and shore up our standing around the globe. 

And to secure necessary aid to help California recover and rebuild from this month‚Äôs tragic wildfires.

I am clear-eyed about the challenges we may face. Our differences can feel extreme at times. And California, I will never back down when our rights are threatened, our values are under attack, or our communities are demonized.

But what unites us as a country is far more important than what divides us. 

We are all in this great enterprise we call America together, and we must succeed together or surely we will fail together.

So let‚Äôs deliver for the American people.

It was my great honor to attend the inauguration of the President of the United States of America. I have deep respect for the office of the President.

While there were many parts of President Trump‚Äôs speech that I disagreed with or found to be inappropriate, I am focused on where we can work together and find common ground.

I agree with the President‚Äôs emphasis on stopping illegal immigration, deporting criminals and targeting the cartels and organized crime profiting from human exploitation at the southern border. These should be shared priorities for our nation.

Although the speech lacked specific details, I welcome the President‚Äôs commitment to ‚Äúrapidly bring down costs and prices,‚Äù and make America ‚Äúa manufacturing nation once again.‚Äù

I share the President‚Äôs lofty and important goal to ‚Äúend the chronic disease epidemic and keep our children, safe, healthy, and disease free.‚Äù

While it is easy to dwell on our disagreements, I am committed to working hard to find common ground to address the challenges we face.

I will stand firm and oppose the President and his party where our views differ, but I will also strive to identify solutions that serve the American people.

We must work together to safeguard our democracy, and I am willing to work with anyone ‚Äì including President Trump and my colleagues on the other side of the aisle ‚Äì to move our country forward and deliver for all of America‚Äôs working families, older Americans, our servicemembers, our veterans, and our children.

I commend President Biden and Vice President Harris for their steadfast leadership, grace, and commitment to ensuring a peaceful transition of power, which is a cornerstone of our democracy. Their administration has worked tirelessly to build a more inclusive and representative nation, and we must continue to build on their progress to restore trust in our democracy, expand opportunity, and improve the lives of all Americans.

To that end, I am committed to working with those who share the goals of lowering costs for everyday Americans, protecting our communities, and advancing the common good. While I will always seek common ground, I will stand firm against the rise of far-right extremism that threatens the safety and well-being of the American people.

Most Americans can find common ground because there is more that unites us than divides us. I strongly believe that more people have faith in the good of our country, and it is our ability to harness this hope and work toward the common good that will strengthen our nation.

Our country is great because of our democracy ‚Äì and our diversity. Every person in this nation deserves the opportunity to realize their dreams and have access to the chance to succeed, regardless of background or circumstance. Everyone should be able to realize their full potential. Fighting for freedom, justice, and equality is at the heart of our nation‚Äôs founding ideals, and we must ensure that these ideals are reflected in the lives of all Americans. Immigrants should not live in fear, members of the LGBTQ community must be able to live their lives free from hate, and women‚Äôs rights and freedoms must be protected. We must also fight for our children and their futures, ensuring they have the opportunities to thrive.

Our country‚Äôs strength is in our unity, and I hope President Trump will work to ensure all Americans are treated with dignity and respect, and that we continue to build a nation where everyone can succeed. The success of all Americans will result in the success of our nation as a whole.

It is morning again in Alaska. With the stroke of a pen, President Trump has sent America and the world the unmistakable message that unleashing Alaska‚Äôs energy and resources will be a top priority of his administration, literally from day 1. 

The contrast with the Biden administration couldn‚Äôt be more stark. For four years, our state suffered under an unrelenting assault‚Äî70 executive orders and actions restricting Alaskans‚Äô economic opportunities and lawful access to our lands. No state has endured this kind of sustained negative attention from a federal administration in recent memory. President Trump‚Äôs sweeping executive order, and the work we will do with his administration over the next four years, will put Alaskans back in the driver‚Äôs seat of our state‚Äôs destiny, advancing critical resource development projects and unleashing economic opportunities for the benefit of our hard-working families and the security of the entire nation.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Four years ago, officers of the law stood their ground to protect Members of Congress and staff as violent insurrectionists stormed the Capitol. These brave officers were beaten, crushed, bear sprayed, maced, and left to defend democracy with their bare hands. 

The halls they protected were desecrated by hate and chaos. Offices ransacked. The electoral count delayed.  

Today, in a grim irony, Donald Trump took the oath of office under the protection of those same officers, standing in those same hallowed halls he incited violence against just four years earlier.

And in one of his first acts, he pardoned the perpetrators and planners of that violence and sedition. 

Trump‚Äôs action today is a sick betrayal of the rule of law and adds grievous insult to injury to law enforcement officers. These men and women fought to uphold the rule of law, only to see it mocked by a man who swore just a few hours ago, to God and country, to defend it. 

It‚Äôs a desecration of memory and the idea of a peaceful transfer of power, and a brazen attempt to rewrite history.

But history will not be rewritten. Not by a thousand lies or a thousand pardons.

Instead, we may be witnessing something worse: the newest milestone along the road to autocracy, in which a president pardons those who do violence on his behalf and encourages others to do the more of the same.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1793, King Louis XVI was executed by guillotine after being convicted of conspiracy with foreign powers and sentenced to death by the French National Convention. 

Louis, who became king in 1774, struggled with the financial crisis inherited from his grandfather. In 1789, he convened the States-General to address the crisis, but the commoner declared itself the National Assembly, sparking the French Revolution. 

Though he initially accepted the revolution, Louis resisted reforms and supported reactionary elements, including his wife, Queen Marie Antoinette. In 1789, a mob forced the royal family to move to Paris, and the king and queen tried to flee to Austria but were captured. Louis was then reduced to a symbolic monarch under the 1791 constitution. The next year, the monarchy was abolished, and Louis was arrested.

text:
This week, we honor the life and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., who reminded us that ‚Äúinjustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.‚Äù His timeless words urge us to rise above division, embrace unity and diversity of thought, and work together to create a nation where justice and opportunity are available to all.

This message is particularly meaningful as we celebrate Unity Week in our community‚Äîa weeklong series of events, conversations, and initiatives that highlight the strength of our community's rich diversity while bringing us together through shared purpose. Unity Week embodies the very principles that Dr. King championed‚Äîjustice, equality, and a collective commitment to lifting one another up. It serves as a powerful reminder that together, we are always stronger. 

Thank you to the Building a Better Bensalem Coalition for organizing this special week and for your dedication to fostering collaboration, understanding, and unity within our community.

As we reflect on the spirit of Unity Week and on Dr. King‚Äôs legacy, may it continue to guide us to lead with integrity, act with purpose, and recommit ourselves to the work of building a brighter, more just, and united future for all.

Congratulations, @secrubio! Since our days sitting side-by-side in the Florida Legislature and serving in the United States Congress, it has been a privilege working with you. Today, I had the honor of attending your welcome ceremony as Secretary of State of the United States. üá∫üá∏

To say I am proud is an understatement.

Throughout your career, you‚Äôve represented our community, our great State of Florida, and our country with distinction. Now, you will represent the American people on the global stage, safeguarding our national security interests. There is no one more qualified for this role.

This marks the beginning of a new era‚Äìone of strength and unapologetic leadership for the United States. It is the day where common sense is once again restored in our government.

Congratulations again! I look forward to working with you to protect our national security and the interests of the American taxpayer.
